kiraly/followers","following_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/following{/other_user}","gists_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/gists{/gist_id}","starred_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/starred{/owner}{/repo}","subscriptions_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/subscriptions","organizations_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/orgs","repos_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/repos","events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/events{/privacy}","received_events_url":"https://api.github.com/users/fkiraly/received_events","type":"User","site_admin":false},"created_at":"2022-09-17T13:46:49Z","updated_at":"2022-09-17T13:47:32Z","author_association":"COLLABORATOR","body":"> then I'm afraid my stats isn't strong enough for a general theorem here haha. Any ideas?\r\n\r\nVariance is additive for any collection of mutually uncorrelated random variables (that have a variance), therefore also for any collection of mutually independent variables (because mutually indendent sets of variables are mutually uncorrelated)\r\n\r\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance#Sum_of_variables\r\nalso see: [BienaymÃ©'s identity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bienaym%C3%A9%27s_identity)\r\n\r\nThis does not cover the form of the distribution though, and for variables not normal the parametric form is in general not preserved. So, while `predict_var` will be correct under the assumption, the remaining methods will be subject to a normal approximation.\r\n\r\n> We could just have a strongly worded disclaimer in the docstring. After all, in my opinion, most users (myself included) are likely using STLForecaster with underyling forecasters that assume normality and uncorrelated residuals.\r\n\r\nAgreed! Should be explained in the docstring (under what assumption correct), and the assumption is probably a common (though often implicit) one.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/sktime/sktime/issues/comments/1250074836/reactions","tota